        "created_at": "2021-01-16T19:13:53.060Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Hi,<br>\nI have been struggling for several month with the problem that signal-desktop is hanging when I receive a new message. It takes then for about 30-60 sec. until the UI becomes responsive again and I can reply to a message.<br>\nWhen I tried to log the issue and started signal-desktop from the terminal, I never experienced this problem. So I found out, that the default command to start signal-desktop from the menu (I downloaded signal-desktop from the official Signal repo, running on Debian testing) includes the flag ‚Äú‚Äìno-sandbox %U‚Äù.</p>\n<p>So my question is, what is this flag doing, and why is default? Shouldn‚Äôt starting the program in a sandbox be more safe?</p>\n<p>Curiously, though, since I removed the --no-sandbox flag signal-desktop works again like a charm, and doesn‚Äôt hang anymore every time I receive a message. Leaving --no-sandbox out significantly improves the usability for me.</p>\n<p>This makes wonder, why is this flag there as default, and what does it actually do?</p>\n<hr>\n<p>Currently running Signal 1.39.5 on Linux 5.10.0-1-amd64 <span class=\"hashtag\">#1</span> SMP Debian 5.10.4-1 (2020-12-31) x86_64 GNU/Linux.</p>",
